<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="15" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[192,1440,374,435]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,374,400]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[563,682,374,400]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lobispinula">
<emphasis box="[563,682,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">lobispinula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a Latin compound name that stems from 
<emphasis box="[1191,1232,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">lobi</emphasis>
(= lobed) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">spinula</emphasis>
(= spine). I refer to the spine near the apex of the phallobasic lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
